  "9.13": "Maha atmanah tu mam partha daiveem prakturam ashritah |\n\nbhajanti ananya manasah jnatva bhuta adim avyam - O Partha, elder of sattvic nature\nPeople, knowing that I am the imperishable cause of all the perishable universes, are me in the same way\nworships\n\nIn the previous verse, Krishna, who described the demonic and demonic nature, is divine here\nDescribes the character. Those of divine nature are always on the path of knowledge, light and truth\nthose who travel They are fortunate to know the Lord. Lord called him \"Mahatma\".\nHe says. God has great love for him. Krishna says “He made me unique\nHe chants with his mind.\" We love God and God loves us\nTo love is the true bhajan. Those who are divine in nature are perishable except the Lord.\nThey know the truth that only God is the eternal truth. God and His in the world\nKnowledge alone is indispensable. Everything else (money, property, gold, power, etc.) is waste. Non-perishable\nWealth is the Lord and His knowledge. Mahatmas are those who think of God in this way.\n\nThe epithet in this verse is 'Partha'. Krishna said to Arjuna, \"Son of Prathea\".\nAddressing means superficial. Etymology from Classical View (₹॥/1301001081//)\nThere is a different spiritual meaning behind this adjective. “Pratha-Vistare' dhatu.Which one\nThat which pervades, that which pervades everywhere is “pratha.” This is the omnipresence of the Lord\nindicates Those who realize the truth that God is omnipresent and see Him everywhere\n'Parthas'. In another sense, the Vedarthabhuta Lord, his qualities, always drink\nThose who do are 'Parthas'. We all should drink Vedartha and become Parthas. Everywhere\nThe idea behind this address is that we should see the all-pervading power within us\nmessage\n\nIn what manner do those of divine nature worship the Lord\nKrishna explains in the next verse.\n\nSatakam kirtayanto maam yatantashascha thamavratah |\nNamaskantashcha Maam Bhaktya Nityayukta Upasate",
