  "11.46": "Kiritinam gadinam cakrahastam ichchami tvam drangtam aham tada eva.\n\nTena eva rupena chatuh bhujena sahasra baho bhava visvamurte-covered, mace-chakra in hand.\nI want to see you in that form. The thousand-armed universe, four again\nAppear with the same form as the arm.\n\n“Your form, quadrupedal, crowned, holding the mace-chakra, as you appeared before\nShow me,” Arjuna pleads with folded hands in the thousand-armed Universal Lord. Here\nArjuna said in Krishna - \"Show your quadrilateral form\". Krishna to his inner devotees\nHe showed his quadrilateral form. Arjuna also saw this. In Bhagavasha-\nIt is said that Krishna manifested his quadrupedal form as a boy:\n\nTamadlu tam balakamambujekshanam chaturbhujam shankhagadadyudayudham,\n\nShrivatsalakshman Galashobhikoustubham Peethambaram Sandrapayodasaubhagam ॥10.03.9॥\nIt is said that Krishna showed the quadrupedal form of Lord which was not seen by common people\nThe verse affirms. Here Arjuna ended his universal darshan in Lord Arjuna\nHe begs to show the quadrilateral form.\nThe main point that we need to know here is: Universal worship of the Lord is common\nImpossible for us. To endure seeing his universal form from the great sage Arjuna himself\nNot done. So can we digest it in our meditation? For this reason\nRather than worshiping the universal form of the Lord in meditation, the universal power of the Lord",
  "11.51": "Arjuna Uvaca-Arjuna said:\n\nDrishtva idam manusham rupam tava soumyam janardana.\n\nIdanim asmi samvrtah sachetah prakrutiam gatah - Janardana, your human form.\nLife came after finding the gentle form. Now recovering and getting back to normal.\n\nHere Arjuna addresses the Lord as Janardhana. Jan-ardana-janardana. Here\nArdana means the one who ends. Many for the word 'people'\nThere are meanings. Jana means bad people. Janardana means destroyer of evil. Jana means born.\nJanardana means liberator of birth. \"To kill the wicked\nI was scared to see that form of you standing. Heeding the call of devotees, to his devotees\nSeeing this gentle form of yours who bestows salvation, I recovered\"- this is the sentiment\nAddressing.\nGod's word\nSudurdarshamidam Rupam Drishtavanasi Yanmama |\n\nDeva apyasya rupasya nityam darshankankshinah 152.\n\nNaham Vedairna Tapasana Danena na Chejya |\nShakya evamvidho drgantam drishtavanasi mam yatha",
  "11.50": "Sanjaya Uwacha- Sanjaya said:\n\nIti arjunam vasudevah tatha uktva swakam rupam darshayam asa bhuyah.\nAshwasayam asa cha bheetam enam bhutva again soumyavapuh mahatma -vasudeva thus\nAfter speaking, he showed his Krishna form to Arjuna. Mahatma Krishna thus returned\nSoumyarupa clapped his hands and comforted Arjuna.\n\nIn this sloka, Sanjaya addresses the Lord as Vasudeva. To this name of the Lord\nThere are many meanings. Vasu-Deva-Vasudeva. Lord Vasu means Himself\nThe closed one. When we cross the fifteen fences of family confinement, the grave\n\nIf you go deep from the state, you see the sixteenth form of life, then that of the Lord\nwill be realised. In this state, the closed Lord opens as God.\nTo see God we must first see ourselves. Without our knowledge\nIt is impossible to see God. When we see our life form, from within\nLord God who is realized. We are aware of our five koshas (annamaya kosha, pranamaya\nKosha, Vigyanmaya Kosha, Manomaya Kosha and Anandamaya Kosha) when on the screen\nAs Vasu; When he comes out of the screen and sees the form of life, he gives darshan as God\nLord Vasudeva.\nArjuna's speech.\nDruchadam manusham roopam tava soumyam janardana |\n\nIdanimasmi samvrtah sachetah prakrutiam gatah",
  "12.5": "klesha adhik tarah tesham avyakta asakta chetsam |\nAvykta hi gatih dukham dehavadlih avapyate--for those who appreciate the worship of impersonality.\nFatigue is high. The path of liberation through the unmanifest is a difficult detour for the practitioner.\n\nShe grants salvation to those who worship Shakti. But the worship of the invisible\nFor those who do \"Adhika Tara Klshesha: - Upasana is very difficult. It leaves the straight path.\nLike traveling to God by a detour. Practitioners have to achieve this with great difficulty.\n\nIn the following verses, Krishna explains how easy it is to worship the Lord directly.\nThis is the easy path of devotion shown to us by the Lord.\n\nYe tu sarvani karmani mayi sannyasya matparah |\nAnanyaneiva Yogena Maam Dhyayanta Upasate",
