  "16.7": "Praddhitam cha Nivritham cha Janah na Viduh Asurah.\n\nna shoucham na api cha acharah na satyam teshu vidyate -Which way do the evil-doers\nKnow what to hold and what to let go. no fold; Not a good move; The bravest of them\nNo word.\n\nHere Krishna describes the social behavior of demoniacs. For those of Asuri nature\nThere is no awareness of what to do and what not to do. From this they\n\nThey are doing what should not be done. Justice and injustice do not matter to them. Making money\nAnd his basic desire is to earn the status of an elite person. Because of this money\nThey do not care that there should be a face of justice in editing.\n\nBasically those of Asura nature lack hygiene. A good word, a good thought,\nClean body is not among them. He pretended to be very clean on the outside\nare living They are never honest. Whatever is done is for show.\nAn example of one of the qualities mentioned in the Krishna Gita can be found in the Mahabharata.\nFor that, the Gita is called the essence of Mahabharata. An excellent example of demonic nature\n\"Duryodhana\".\n\nHow do these demoniacs become social thorn, what is their understanding? This\nIn the next part of the chapter, Krishna elaborates.",
  "16.4": "Dambhah darpah abhimanah cha krodhah parushyam evacha.\nAjyanam cha abhijatasya partha sampadam asurim- partha, demonic wealth [bad manners]\nThe qualities of the native are: hypocrisy, arrogance, jealousy, anger, rudeness and rudeness.\n\nIn contrast to the twenty-six divine qualities mentioned above, Krishna has six demonic qualities in this verse\nsaid:\n\n(1) Dambha (pretending to be something that is not): As if what is not there is inside\nA display of goodness; Acting like a very good person hiding the evil inside\nDoing, etc. seems presumptuous. This is the opposite quality of Arjavam mentioned above.\n(2) Darpa: An attitude of aversion to doing anything wrong. This is the opposite of the virtue of Hri.\n\n(3) Atimana (09 868/7800 08 56): excessive idea of ​​oneself; I am a big man\nBeing delusional and disrespectful to another; That everyone should hold his leg\nDesires—these are superhuman.\n\n(4) Anger: Anger is a bad quality that cannot be left even if a person wants to let it go. It's like we don't know\nA vice that leads us astray.\n\n(5) Parushya: Fierce, nasty speech; To speak kindly of another,\netc. Example for Parushya.\n\n(6) Ignorance: Ignorance is the ruler of all the above vices. A true sage is never this bad\nDo not become a slave of qualities.\n\nAll these demonic qualities make their home in us and drive us out. So this\nWe have to get rid of vices first. In the Qur'an it is - \"The 14a 07077 08! 1017 51098\n508 03%A 0001 61067 08” beautifully said. Throw yourself out, sit inside yourself\nThey say first get rid of these vices that are ruining you. This is what the Vedas say\nSaid thus: “Yo asmaan vehti yam vayam dwishtih” ..|[Atharva 3-27-2|- ie-\n“He who hates us, the enemy whom we hate\nIt means to push.” The enemy here is our internal enemies, these vices.\n\nThe epithet 'Partha' is used in this verse. “We turn away from vices,\nThis is the message that one should go on the path of knowledge and live a true life\nis behind the adjective.\n\nDivine Sampad Vimokshaya Nibandhaya 8suri Mata |\nMa Shuchah Sampadam Daiveemabhijatohsi Pandava",
